Checkpoints.

A checkpoint is a tile the player walks onto to set a safety net: if they later take a fatal hit, they're sent back to the checkpoint instead of losing the game. It's the entity for marking progress through a dangerous map — claim a checkpoint, and a death that would otherwise end the run returns the player to that spot with full health. A checkpoint hums a quiet loop so the player can hear it, and it's claimed the instant they step onto it.

A checkpoint is the death-recovery marker. Its sibling, the spawnpoint, sets where the player first appears and reappears when a map loads fresh; see the spawnpoints topic for that side of the same idea.

How a checkpoint works.

A checkpoint sits on a single tile. While it's there, it plays an ambient loop on a repeating beat so the player can find it by ear. When the player steps onto its tile, it plays a claim cue, becomes the player's active checkpoint, and disappears from the map — its job, registering this spot as the return point, is done in that one touch.

A checkpoint only matters on the player's last life. With lives to spare, a fatal hit simply costs a life and the player keeps going, and the checkpoint isn't consulted. On the last life, instead of ending the run, the player is returned to the tile of the checkpoint they most recently claimed, restored to full health, with the map reloaded around them. If the player never claimed a checkpoint, that final death ends in the usual try-again prompt. Only the most recently claimed checkpoint is active, so claiming a new one replaces the old as the return point — letting you move the safety net forward as the player advances.

Checkpoint fields.

The checkpoint form takes the following:

Coordinates. An x and y (and z on 3d maps) — the tile the player steps onto to claim the checkpoint.

Speed. Milliseconds between plays of the ambient loop that marks the checkpoint's position, so a smaller number makes a more insistent beacon.

Checkpoint sound (a folder name from the checkpoint sounds list, or none). The audio theme; the bundle supplies a get clip (played when the checkpoint is claimed) and a loop clip (the ambient bed). Pick none for a silent checkpoint.

Looping sound (checkbox). Off by default, where the ambient loop replays on the beat set by speed. Turn it on to play the loop continuously instead, with no gap and no restarting, which suits a longer ambient clip that the repeating beat would otherwise cut short. The speed only matters when this is off.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the checkpoint sound list is focused in the form, press space to hear the loop clip of the highlighted theme and hold control and press L to hear its get clip.

Authoring checkpoints by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a checkpoint is: checkpoint x y speed checktype looping. On 3d maps a z follows y: checkpoint x y z speed checktype looping. The speed is a whole number of milliseconds, the checkpoint sound must match a checkpoint sounds folder name or the word none, and looping is true or false — true plays the ambient loop continuously, false replays it on the speed beat.
